'''''Knight Lore''''' is a 1984 [[action-adventure game]] developed and published by [[Ultimate Play the Game]], and written by company founders [[Chris and Tim Stamper]]. The game is known for its use of [[Isometric graphics in video games and pixel art|isometric graphics]], which it further popularized in video games. In ''Knight Lore'', the [[player character]] [[Sabreman]] has forty days to collect objects throughout a castle and brew a cure to his [[werewolf|werewolf curse]]. Each castle room is depicted in [[monochrome]] on [[flip-screen|its own screen]] and consists of blocks to climb, obstacles to avoid, and puzzles to solve.

Ultimate released ''Knight Lore'' third in the Sabreman series but later claimed to have completed it first and withheld its release for a year to position the company advantageously in anticipation of the game's effect on the market. ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} novel [[image masking]] technique, [[Filmation engine|Filmation]], let images appear to pass atop and behind each other without [[Collision detection|their contents colliding]]. This created the illusion of depth priority, which the computer did not natively support. By delaying ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} release, Ultimate protected sales of their then-upcoming ''[[Sabre Wulf]]'' and created [[Alien 8|another Filmation game]] before other developers could [[video game clone|copy]] the style. Ultimate released the original ''Sabreman'' trilogy in quick succession in 1984 for the [[ZX Spectrum]]. ''Knight Lore'' came last, in November. [[Porting of video games|Ports]] followed for the [[BBC Micro]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[MSX]], and [[Family Computer Disk System]]. 

''Knight Lore'' is regarded as a seminal work in British video game history and has been included in multiple lists of top Spectrum games. Critics considered its technical solutions and [[isometric 3D]] style a harbinger of future game design. They praised the game's controls and atmosphere of mystery, but noted its [[difficulty level|difficult gameplay]] and criticised its sound and occasional graphical slowdown. ''Knight Lore'' was named the 1984 [[game of the year]] by the [[Golden Joystick Awards]] and ''[[Popular Computing Weekly]]'' readers. Though it was not the first isometric 3D video game, ''Knight Lore'' popularised the format. When the isometric, flip-screen style fell out of fashion, ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} influence persisted in computer role-playing games. Retrospective reviewers remember the game as the first to offer an exploratory "world" rather than a flat surface, but consider its controls outdated and frustrating in the thirty years since its release.

The game was later included in compilations including [[Rare (company)|Rare]]'s 2015 [[Xbox One]] retrospective compilation, ''[[Rare Replay]]''.

== Gameplay ==
[[File:Knight lore 3.gif|thumb|left|alt=A man with a darkened face in a pith hat stands atop several rows of blocks. The image is in isometric display such that we can see three sides of the blocks but only one side of the character (who is displayed in two dimensions). The gameplay area is displayed in monochrome: bright pink and black for positive and negative space, respectively. Some brick façade in the background bound the room and two archways show ways to exit the room. Below the scene is a heads-up display drawn with the motif of an unrolled scroll. There are icons to denote player lives, with a smaller version of the character, a potion bottle item, and indicators for the day and time: "DAY 02" in a scripted typeface, and an arched rectangle with a sun image peeking from the rectangle's left horizon. |Sabreman atop a stack of blocks in a ZX Spectrum screenshot. Daytime is beginning in the indicator at the bottom right. ''Knight Lore''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s gameplay area is depicted in [[monochrome]] to avoid [[attribute clash]].{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}}]]

The player, as Sabreman, has been bitten by the Sabre Wulf and now transforms into a [[werewolf]] at nightfall.{{sfn|Hunt|2010|p=28}} He has 40 days to collect items throughout Melkhior the Wizard's castle{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006b|p=76}} and brew a cure for his curse. An onscreen timer shows the progression of day into night, when Sabreman metamorphoses into a werewolf, returning to human form at sunrise.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}} Some of the castle's monsters only attack Sabreman when he is a werewolf.{{sfn|Parrish|2007}} The [[game over|game ends]] if the player completes the potion or does not finish the task in forty days.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}} The game's only directions are given through a poem included with the game's cassette tape.{{sfn|''Computer and Video Games''|1985a}}

The castle consists of a series of 128 rooms,{{sfn|''Amtix''|1985}} each displayed on a single, non-scrolling screen.{{sfn|Parrish|2007}} Sabreman must navigate the 3D maze of stone blocks in each room, usually to retrieve a collectible object, whilst avoiding spikes and enemies, which kill him on contact. The player starts with five [[Health (gaming)|lives]], and loses one for each death; running out of lives ends the game. Stone blocks serve as platforms for the player to jump between; some fall under the player's weight, some move of their own accord, and some can be pushed by enemies or Sabreman.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}} Sabreman jumps higher when in werewolf form, which helps in specific puzzles.{{sfn|Hunt|2010|p=28}} The player often needs to move blocks to reach distant objects, which are then used as platforms to reach areas in other puzzles.{{sfn|''Computer and Video Games''|1985a}} To complete the game, the player must return 14 sequential objects from throughout the castle to the wizard's cauldron room.{{sfn|''Amtix''|1985}}{{sfn|''Amstrad Action''|1985}} At the end of the game, the player receives a final [[score (game)|score]] based on the remaining time and amount of the quest completed.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}}

== Development ==
[[Ultimate Play the Game]], represented by its co-founding brothers, [[Tim and Chris Stamper]], was uncommonly taciturn in matters of press and marketing, though they provided some details on ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} development to ''[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]'' magazine.{{sfn|Hunt|2010|p=28}}{{sfn|Hunt|2010|p=24}}{{sfn|Kean|1988}} While ''Knight Lore'' was released as the third game in the Sabreman series, the Stamper brothers later claimed to have finished it first,{{sfn|Hunt|2010|p=28}}{{sfn|Parrish|2007}} saying they withheld the game for about a year for market reasons: they thought that ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} advancements—copyrighted as the [[Filmation engine]]—would hurt sales of their then-upcoming ''[[Sabre Wulf]]'', and used the extra time to prepare another Filmation game (''[[Alien 8]]'') to preempt the sales that would be lost when other publishers would try to [[video game clone|copy the technique]].{{sfn|Hunt|2010|pp=28–29}} Tim Stamper recalled that "we just had to sit on it because everyone else was so far behind".{{sfn|Hunt|2010|pp=28–29}} More recent research has suggested this may have been an exaggeration as the coding routines found in ''Knight Lore'' are far more optimised than those used in the earlier games.{{sfn|Carroll|2012}} ''Sabre Wulf'' was released to commercial and critical success in 1984. The next two Sabreman titles—''[[Underwurlde]]'' and ''Knight Lore''—followed in close succession before the end of the year.{{sfn|Hunt|2010|pp=28–30}}

[[File:Sprite rendering by binary image mask.png|thumb|In image masking, the developer adds a hole and then fills in its details.|alt=This diagram shows two vertical image progressions. The first two images of each are (1) a Sim City-like overhead, pixel art view of a city, and (2) a ghost and Pac-Man-like character image. The first progression juxtaposes the cityscape against silhouetted cut-outs of the characters, with the word "AND" in-between the two. It results in a composite image of the silhouetted cut-outs atop the image of the cityscape. The second progression juxtaposes the previous image (the silhouettes atop the city) against an image with un-silhouetted characters in color, with the word "OR" in-between the two. It results in a composite image where the full-color characters fill in the silhouetted cut-out holes.]]

Filmation and ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} graphical novelty lay in how images could render without overlapping.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=22}} Filmation introduced "masked [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]]" whereas earlier games used "planar sprites",{{sfn|Stafford|1986}} which overlapped without regard for depth order. Chris Stamper's solution was to use [[Mask (computing)#Image masks|image masking]]. A mask is a version of an image that defines a background from the subject matter in different colours. When [[logical conjunction|combining]] the mask and the on-screen composite image, the mask's "background" data was ignored and a hole in the shape of the desired image sprite was added to the background. This was filled in with the sprite's details. Thus, rooms in ''Knight Lore'' were drawn one sprite at a time through this masking method. In more recent times, contemporary images render with layer priority set at the individual pixel level.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=22}} ''Knight Lore'' is depicted in [[monochrome]] that changes between rooms so as to avoid [[attribute clash]], a computing limitation wherein an object's colour interfered with those of others in close proximity.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}}

Ultimate released ''Knight Lore'' for the [[ZX Spectrum]] in November 1984. In a press release, they announced the game as the beginning of a new class of adventure games and "the very pinnacle of software development on the 48K Spectrum".{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=21}} As standard for the cryptic company, Ultimate did not circulate screenshots of the game in its press materials or cover art.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=21}} ''Knight Lore'' was subsequently released for the [[BBC Micro]], [[Amstrad CPC]], and [[MSX]] later in 1985.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=24}} The Amstrad version upgraded the monochromatic colouring to a two-colour foreground setup.{{sfn|''Amtix''|1985}} [[Jaleco]] released versions of ''Knight Lore'' for MSX{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=26}} and, later, the [[Famicom Disk System]].{{sfn|''Famitsu''|n.d.|ps=}} The latter 1986 release barely resembled its namesake.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=25}} Ultimate asked Shahid Ahmad, who developed the ''Knight Lore''-inspired ''[[Chimera (video game)|Chimera]]'' (1985), to develop a ''Knight Lore'' port for the [[Commodore 64]], but this did not come to fruition.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=24}} ''Knight Lore'' later appeared in the Spectrum version of the 1986 compilation ''They Sold a Million II''{{sfn|Rignall|1986}} and the 2015 [[Xbox One]] compilation of 30 Ultimate and Rare titles ''[[Rare Replay]]''.{{sfn|McWhertor|2015}}

