''Knight Lore'' entered the UK video game charts in the week up to 8 November 1984 while ''Underwurlde'' was still number 1,{{sfn|RAM/C|1984a}} and went on to replace its predecessor at the top of the charts the following week.{{sfn|RAM/C|1984b}} By the start of 1985 it had been succeeded by [[Ghostbusters (1984 video game)|''Ghostbusters'']].{{sfn|RAM/C|1985}}

Computer game magazines lauded ''Knight Lore'',{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=22}} writing that its graphics were the first of its kind and marked a [[Sea change (idiom)|sea change]] from its contemporaries.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}}{{sfn|''Computer and Video Games''|1985a}}{{sfn|Bourne|1985}}{{sfn|''Your Spectrum''|1985|ps=. Component scores were 5/5, 5/5, and 4/5.}} ''[[Computer & Video Games]]'' (''CVG'') wrote that they had never seen graphics of its calibre and that it lived up to Ultimate's hype. Peter Sweasey of ''Home Computing Weekly'' was left speechless and predicted that ''Knight Lore'' would change the market. ''Crash'' said it was unlikely to be surpassed as the Spectrum's best game.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=22}} ''Crash'' selected ''Knight Lore'' as a "Crash Smash" recommendation in its January 1985 issue.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}} ''[[Popular Computing Weekly]]'' readers named ''Knight Lore'' their 1984 arcade game and overall [[game of the year]].{{sfn|''Popular Computing Weekly''|1985}} ''Knight Lore'' was also named ''CVG''{{'s}} game of the year at their 1985 [[Golden Joystick Awards]] event, and Ultimate was named both developer and programmer of the year.{{sfn|''Computer and Video Games''|1985b}}

<!-- atmosphere, environment -->''Knight Lore''{{'s}} atmosphere, which ''[[Sinclair User]]'' described as a "crepuscular world of claustrophobic menace", inspired many curious questions on the part of the adventurer in contemporaneous 1985 reviews.{{sfn|Bourne|1985}} ''Crash'' appreciated the imaginative mystery of the game as they attempted to answer why Sabreman turns into a werewolf, who they preferred to play as, and what the collectible objects throughout the castle do.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}} Sabreman's werewolf transformation sequence, in particular, annoyed ''CVG''{{sfn|''Computer and Video Games''|1985a}} and traumatised players, according to ''Well Played'', a book of academic [[close reading]]s of video games, as players empathised with the suffering Sabreman.{{sfn|Garcia-Panella|2010}} The game design gave the impression that the castle was far grander in scale than it was in reality,{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006b|p=75}} and ''Crash'' wrote that the game's novel eight-way direction scheme suited the 3D space.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}} ''Crash'' compared ''Knight Lore'' stylistically to the 1984 ''[[Avalon (video game)|Avalon]]'', but suggested that the former had bolder visuals. The magazine preferred ''Knight Lore'' to its predecessor (''Underwurlde'') and one critic even considered the former to be Ultimate's best game.{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}}

<!-- technical audiovisual -->''Crash'' noted how ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} masking technique addressed issues of [[Flicker (screen)|flicker]] and attribute clash,{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}} and ''[[Sinclair User]]'' appreciated how Sabreman disappeared from view when passing behind blocks.{{sfn|Bourne|1985}} In criticism, reviewers considered ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} sound to be its weakest component,{{sfn|''Computer and Video Games''|1985a}}{{sfn|''Amstrad Action''|1985}} though ''Your Spectrum'' and ''Crash'' also identified the sometimes cruel difficulty of its gameplay.{{sfn|''Your Spectrum''|1985|ps=. Component scores were 5/5, 5/5, and 4/5.}}{{sfn|''Crash''|1985}} Later rooms of the castle require pixel-perfect precision, compounded by the anxiety of the running timer,{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006b|p=76}} and the game's animations would slow down proportional to the degree of onscreen action.{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006b|p=77}}

<!-- port differences -->In reviews of the Amstrad release, ''[[Amtix]]'' noted the colour additions over the monochromatic original and wrote that ''Knight Lore'' was among the Amstrad's best adventures. Their one complaint was the graphical slowdown when too many elements were moving onscreen.{{sfn|''Amtix''|1985}} ''[[Amstrad Action]]'' shared this complaint but nevertheless named ''Knight Lore'' among the Amstrad's best three games—an improvement on the Spectrum release and on par with the quality of Commodore 64 titles.{{sfn|''Amstrad Action''|1985}}

== Legacy ==
[[File:ZXSpectrum48k.jpg|thumb|Critics named ''Knight Lore'' among the best games for the ZX Spectrum.|alt=A black, rectangular, and plastic console with "Sinclair" in raised, thin, and wide lettering. A keyboard is built into the unit. Its keys are light gray and Chicklet-sized with white lettering. Near each key are three abbreviated functions written in all capital letters and in three colors: white, green, and red.]]

''Knight Lore'' is widely regarded as a seminal work in British gaming history.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}}{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=21}} According to Kieron Gillen of ''[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]'', ''Knight Lore'' is second only to ''[[Elite (video game)|Elite]]'' (1984) as an icon of the 1980s British computer game industry.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}} British magazine ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' described players' first impressions of ''Knight Lore'' as "unforgettable", on par with the experience of playing ''[[Space Harrier]]'' (1985), ''[[Wolfenstein 3D]]'' (1992), or ''[[Super Mario 64]]'' (1996) for the first time.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|pp=21–22}} ''Retro Gamer'' recalled that ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} striking, isometric 3D visuals were both a bold advance in game graphics and a foretelling of their future.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=21}} British magazine ''[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]'' described the game's graphics engine as "the single greatest advance in the history of video games",{{sfn|Davison|2013}} and ''Retro Gamer'' compared the engine's impact to that of [[sound film|the introduction of sound in film]].{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006a|p=29}} ''Knight Lore'' was not the first to use isometric graphics—earlier examples include ''[[Zaxxon]]'' (1982), ''[[Q*bert]]'' (1982), and ''[[Ant Attack]]'' (1983){{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=22}}{{sfn|Signor|2014}}—but its graphic style and large in-game world{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006b|p=74}} further popularised the technique and put Ultimate and Filmation in its epicentre.{{sfnm|Carroll|2014|1p=22|Signor|2014|Kumar|2010}}

Several [[video game clone]]s were inspired by ''Knight Lore''. When programmers at [[Edge Games|The Edge]] struggled to replicate the isometric style, visiting developer [[Bo Jangeborg]] devised his own solution. The result, ''[[Fairlight (video game)|Fairlight]]'' (1985), is regarded as another classic of the platform. The Edge's version of Filmation received its own branding as "Worldmaker".{{sfn|Carroll|2014|pp=22–23}} Shahid Ahmad said Firebird's ''Chimera'' (1985) was even closer to ''Knight Lore''. Ahmad's "shock" and "admiration" from playing ''Knight Lore'' reportedly changed his life and convinced him to continue making games. He released ''Chimera'' on the Amstrad CPC, [[Atari 8-bit]], Commodore 64, and ZX Spectrum, customising each [[Porting of video games|port]] for the processing limitations of its hardware.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=23}} By 1986, many British video game publishers had produced ''Knight Lore''-style isometric games; examples include ''[[Sweevo's World]]'', ''[[Movie (video game)|Movie]]'', ''[[Quazatron]]'', ''[[Get Dexter]]'', ''[[Glider Rider (video game)|Glider Rider]]'', ''[[Molecule Man (video game)|Molecule Man]]'',{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=24}} ''[[Spindizzy (video game)|Spindizzy]]'', and ''[[Bobby Bearing]]''.{{sfn|Retro Gamer|2006b|p=76}} Many of these titles suffered the same slowdown issues as ''Knight Lore'' due to too much on-screen activity.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=24}}

Ultimate itself released four more Filmation games. ''Alien 8'' (1985) was rushed for release before developers had an opportunity to react to ''Knight Lore'', though ''Retro Gamer'' said that its rush was not noticeable, as ''Alien 8'' had a larger game world than ''Knight Lore'', with even more puzzles.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=23}} ''Alien 8'' and ''Knight Lore'' are similar in gameplay, but the former is set in [[outer space]].{{sfn|Hunt|2010|p=29}} With the updated Filmation II engine, ''[[Nightshade (1985 video game)|Nightshade]]'' (1985) added colour and scrolling graphics (in place of [[flip-screen]] room changes{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=24}}); however, ''Retro Gamer'' regarded its gameplay as comparatively dull. ''[[Gunfright]]'' (1986), reported as the Stampers' last game, also used Filmation II and was more robust than its predecessor. ''[[Pentagram (video game)|Pentagram]]'' (1986) returned to flip-screen rooms and its action-based gameplay included shooting enemies. It sold poorly and was the last Sabreman game.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=23}} Meanwhile, the Stamper brothers sought to enter the burgeoning console industry. They sold Ultimate to [[U.S. Gold]] in the mid-1980s and established [[Rare (company)|Rare]] to develop [[Nintendo]] console games. While Ultimate's last two isometric games were of lesser quality, consumer interest in the genre endured.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=26}}

The isometric, flip-screen trend continued in Britain for several years. Apart from ''Fairlight'', ''Sweevo's World'' and ''Get Dexter'', other isometric flip-screen games included [[Jon Ritman]]'s ''Knight Lore''-inspired ''[[Batman (1986 video game)|Batman]]'' (1986), ''[[Head over Heels (video game)|Head over Heels]]'' (1987), ''[[The Last Ninja]]'' (1987), ''[[La Abadía del Crimen]]'' (1987), ''[[Cadaver (video game)|Cadaver]]'' (1990), and console games ''[[Solstice (1990 video game)|Solstice]]'' (1990){{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=25}} and ''[[Landstalker]]'' (1992).{{sfn|Signor|2014}} As players grew tired of the genre's similar reiterations, Ritman's games, in particular, brought new ideas.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=25}} Sandy White, who developed the pre-''Knight Lore'' isometric game ''Ant Attack'', was impressed by Ultimate's in-game "balance" and gutsy design decisions.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=27}} The developer of ''[[The Great Escape (1986 video game)|The Great Escape]]'', another isometric game, considered ''Knight Lore'' to be more "a rival title than an inspiration", but it still spurred him to spend nine months making ''[[Where Time Stood Still]]''.{{sfn|Carroll|2014|pp=25–26}} ''Retro Gamer'' wrote that ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} influence persisted 30 years later through titles such as ''[[Populous (video game)|Populous]]'' (1989), ''[[Syndicate (1993 video game)|Syndicate]]'' (1993), ''[[UFO: Enemy Unknown]]'' (1994), and ''[[Civilization II]]'' (1996).{{sfn|Carroll|2014|p=27}} The style also spread to computer role-playing games like ''[[Baldur's Gate (video game)|Baldur's Gate]]'', ''[[Planescape: Torment]]'', ''[[Diablo (video game)|Diablo]]'', and ''[[Fallout (video game)|Fallout]]''.{{sfn|Signor|2014}} Though ''GamesRadar''{{'s}} Matt Cundy reported in 2009 that isometric perspective was no longer as prominent a topic in game design,{{sfn|Cundy|2009}} in 2014, Chris Scullion of ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' traced ''Knight Lore''{{'s}} isometric influence to ''[[The Sims 4]]'' (2014) and ''[[Diablo III]]'' (2012).{{sfn|Scullion|2015}}

''Knight Lore'' was included in multiple lists of top Spectrum games{{sfn|''Your Sinclair''|1991}}{{sfn|''Your Sinclair''|1993|ps=. #22 and #33, respectively.}}{{sfn|Whitehead|n.d.|ps=}} and top games for any platform.{{sfn|''Next Generation''|1996|ps=. #88.}} It inspired two [[fangame]]s: a 1999 sequel{{sfn|''PC Zone''|1999}} and a 2010 3D [[remake]], which was in development for four years.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}}{{sfn|''Retro Gamer''|2010}}{{sfn|Caoili|2010}}

Though isometric games had existed previously, in a retrospective review, Gillen (''Rock, Paper, Shotgun'') recalled that ''Knight Lore'' was the first game to offer a "world" with physical depth for exploration as opposed to the simple mechanics of arcade games.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}} Jeremy Signor of ''[[USgamer]]'' agreed that ''Knight Lore'' felt more like a world than a painting and added that the game's innovative use of successive, single-screen rooms ("flip-screen") pre-dated ''[[The Legend of Zelda]]'' by years.{{sfn|Signor|2014}} Gillen said the game's punishing style (unforgiving gameplay, high difficulty, awkward controls) had become obsolete in the 30 years since its release and criticised ''Knight Lore'' as "enormously innovative, incredibly atmospheric, and totally unplayable", suggesting that the similar ''Head over Heels'' (1987) had aged much better.{{sfn|Gillen|2010}} Peter Parrish (''Eurogamer''), too, found the game frustrating, though well-made.{{sfn|Parrish|2007}} Dan Whitehead of the same publication appreciated that the 2015 ''Rare Replay'' compilation version of ''Knight Lore'' [[Video game console emulator|emulated]] the original's choppy animations as the ZX Spectrum's processor once struggled to render the onscreen objects.{{sfn|Whitehead|2015}}

